Multiple sclerosis: it's not just medication that matters, it's also the patient's will to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease and a person with this diagnosis needs the care of a number of specialists: neurologist, physiotherapist, ergotherapist, urologist, ophthalmologist, psychologist, psychiatrist and many other specialists.
However, it is not only about treatment care, for example women with multiple sclerosis need consultations, if they decide to have a child, care for these patients includes social legal advice, recommendations on housing treatment, etc.
Yet all of this is not enough: the development of the disease can be fundamentally influenced by the patient himself.
The more he fights the disease actively, the longer he can work and may not fundamentally change his lifestyle.
As doctors point out, the patient’s passivity frees up space for disease activity.
For example, it is shown that regular movement considerably delays the time when the sick person needs some compensation aid, such as a cane.
It is important that patients and their surroundings are not subject to various myths, such as that the disease automatically leads them to end up in a wheelchair.
That's why the Give a Chance page was created (www.bezmytu.cz), which is supported by the ongoing media campaign Give a Chance.
The most important person in the care of the sick with multiple sclerosis is neurologist.
In multiple sclerosis, twice the saying that the disease begins to be treated sooner, the more likely something can be affected by the doctor.
It's because we have medicines for multiple sclerosis in an inflammatory stage when the process of neurodegeneration is not yet so powerful.
The sooner we intervene, the greater the hope that we will be able to stop and delay disability, explains MUDr. Eva Medová from the Neurology Clinic of the General Faculty Hospital in Prague.
It is very important in people with multiple sclerosis rehabilitation care, which most often resolves the weakening of the lower limbs or disturbances of balance.
Patients are treated according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, improve walking, strengthen the pelvic floor, reduce swallowing disorders or improve coordination.
"It is really individual, depending on the specific problems of the patient," says MUDr. Martina Kövári, head of the Department of Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine of the University Hospital in Motol.
People with multiple sclerosis suffer from the same disease, but it manifests itself in a different way for everyone.
Rehabilitation can't stop the disease, but it can always ease its symptoms.
Movement activity, however, also strengthens the immune state of the organism, which is desirable in the case of multiple sclerosis.
Another positive of regular exercise is the fact that the sick are verifying what they can do, and that strengthens their confidence.
"The endorphins are washed out during the exercise, and one feels good about it," says PhDr. Kamila Řásová from the Clinic of Rehabilitation Medicine at the Royal Vinohrady University Hospital.
By influencing the physical side, we act on the limbic system responsible for emotions.
We directly interfere with the psyche and immune processes and stabilize the disease, adds.
"These patients have previously been so-called spared, today we know that they need a targeted burden," says Professor PaedDr. Pavel Kolář, head of the Department of Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine of the University Hospital in Motol.
Physiotherapy is intended to enable a person to remain self-sufficient for as long as possible, including job assignments.
Physiotherapists therefore work with ergotherapists to get each person a compensation aid tailored to him.
Many patients also need the care of a psychologist or a psychiatrist.
They're in a difficult situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, it usually shakes people up.
They're in shock, panic, fear.
They must respond to a great burden - loss of health.
With a sore soul like this, we're supposed to go to someone, not try to carry everything on our own shoulders.
"I work with them in such a way that they eventually conclude that even with handicap you can live a full life and that multiple sclerosis does not mean the end of life," says psychotherapist Renata Malinová - Schubertová from the Neurological Clinic of the General Faculty Hospital in Prague.
