They discovered traces of settlement by a modern man from different times, including murals, tool residue and so on and so forth.
In a layer of 23A, which according to the instruments dating back about 30,000 years ago, scientists discovered but something that very much resembles the remains of a breakfast buffet.
There were traces of oatmeal grains found on the site, which apparently passed through the process of producing today such popular flakes.
With it today, the grains are soaked first, then dried, removed from the cover, so-called pluch, then spat and pressed flat.
In the cave of Paglicci it was possible to discover grains that were apparently heated or steamed, and then probably crushed between two millstones - at least there are traces of use on two stones in the cave.
Thus, scientists could not demonstrate in their publication for the magazine PNAS that there was a complete process of production of flakes in the cave, but the similarity is indeed very striking.
We also have no evidence of how people could eat flakes, but the assumption that it was with some liquid and possibly even warm is, of course, entirely logical.
At the same time, it is a very interesting proof of how intensive people used cereals long before agriculture.
If the flake interpretation is correct, the oldest flakes overtaken agriculture by about 20,000 years.
