At its most anticipated meeting over the years, federal reserve legislators will spend two days this week sitting at the 27-foot Honduran Mahogany table, deciding whether after nearly ten years it is time to raise the key interest rate.
Standing over them at one end of the central bank ornament, the two-story meeting room will be a wall painting of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues are to put the economic interests of the nation above everything else.
The central bank has a double charge from Congress: maximize US employment and keep prices stable here.
But since the Great Recession, Fed officials have acknowledged that there is an unwritten third term: financial stability.
And this third term of office could be the X-factor too close to the foreseeable decision to be announced on Thursday as to whether the US economy is ready to launch an offsetting from an unprecedented stimulus in the form of almost zero short-term interest rates on the spot since the end of 2008.
Although most data show solid economic growth, recent turbulence in world financial markets could already scare the Fed into adding volatility by increasing its federal fund reference rate - even by no more than a quarter of a percentage point.
"It is clear that the labour market and inflation will primarily be the most important thing to follow," said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist of Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"But I think they were just looking for an excuse not to increase the rate, the increased uncertainty surrounding the global market already gives them sufficient justification to wait further," she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself is causing nervousness in the financial markets.
About half of the economists recently asked by Blomberg predicted a rate increase this week.
However, financial markets expect the Fed to delay the issue, with only a key indicator of about 30% chance of an increase.
This would point to a decline in the stock market if the Fed raises rates only if politicians soften the downturn by promising that further increases are in sight.
On Tuesday, the industrial average of Dow Jones jumped by 228.89 points, or 1.4%, at 16,599,85.
The meeting was triggered by the expectation that Fed politicians would hold their rates calm this week, says John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be a surprise if the Fed now raised rates," he says.
If Fed politicians did this, "they would have to go to the limit in their programming statement and hold hands with the financial markets so that they wouldn't panic."
Other experts argued that raising rates would calm the financial markets, as it would remove uncertainty about how the Fed would proceed.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed to be on the right track to raise the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of economic recovery in the US.
Yellen said that despite spring and early summer, she expects rates to rise this year, despite complaints from liberals, that more economic progress is needed.
Although job creation slowed down in August, the labour market has seen solid growth this year.
The unemployment rate has fallen to 5.1% in the previous month, which is the lowest in more than seven years and is close to what the Fed considers to be full employment.
Wage profits showed signs of lifting.
And while inflation continues to take place below the annual 2% target of the central bank, Fed politicians claim that the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the tightness of the labour market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist of Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world began to break down at the end of last month after China devalued its currency.
Dow Jones’s industrial average dropped 16% below its record value in May, when investors feared that slowing China’s economy would bring global growth down.
The market somewhat bounced this month and Dow is now losing only almost 10% of the May peak.
To the Fed’s policy makers, the troubled market situation provides a comprehensive calculation of the start of an interest rate increase.
"In the absence of what happened in the financial markets, and reports of the weakness of the Chinese economy in the last few weeks, this meeting would have been tightened up," said Stephen D. Oliner, UCLA researcher Ziman Center for Real Estate and former Fed official.
They now predict that they will wait at least a month to gain better control of the consequences.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about the impact this will have on the US economy, and they have almost no data to rely on about the latest developments in China," Oliner said.
The state of health of the global economy is not one of the Fed’s main interests, so it should technically not be included in their decision-making.
But in fact, the Fed has become the monetary authority of the world.
The central bank’s influence in recent years has been enormous.
A mere hint of the then president Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could "shrink" their monetary expansion on the market, triggered convulsions around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly closely linked, Fed leaders can be expected to follow developments elsewhere, but they also consult other central bankers and experts to better read the state of the global economy.
Their decision-making process is "more art than science," said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy for the wealth-management of Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Va, noted this month that "The Fed has a history of excessive movements in financial markets that seem unrelated to economic fundamentals."
Lacker, a voting member of the open-market Federal Committee’s policy making, pushed to raise rates, quoted the 1998-99 decision as an example.
The financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to reduce its reference rate by 0.75 percentage point during three meetings "Despite the limited identifiable effects on growth in the US," said Lacker.
A year later, Fed officials reversed these cuts.
The Fed should give priority to concerns about financial stability only during a major crisis, such as the 2008 market collapse, said Adam Posen S., a former member of the Committee setting rates at the Bank of England.
The latest turmoil is not even close to this level, he said.
