For mildly obese diabetics, weight loss surgery could be useful
The benefits of weight loss surgery for slightly obese people with type 2 diabetes can last at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is still too early to say whether mildly obese people with type 2 diabetes live longer after weight loss surgery than those receiving non-surgical treatment.
"The mortality data take a long time to show," says Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight loss surgery who wrote an editorial on a new study of JAMA surgery.
Surgery for weight loss, bariatric surgery use different methods to reduce stomach.
Reduce hunger and limit the human body to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proved effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most of the survey has been conducted in people with morbid obesity with a body weight index (BMI) of 25 or higher.
BMI, which measures the height-related weight relationship, is considered normal in values between 18,5 and 24,9.
BMI values of 25 or higher indicate overweight and people above 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For their new studies, researchers from the Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan have used data collected from a study since 2007 that deals with two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and gastricectomy - in treatment procedures of type 3 diabetes in people who were mildly obese.
The average BMI among those undergoing surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 at the end of their fifth year, according to a study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of those who have not received surgical treatment for diabetes remained roughly the same at 29.
Among patients with surgery, diabetes was resolved completely in 36 percent and partly in 28 cases.
In the treatment group, only 1 percent of patients were fully resolved to compare diabetes and in part only about 2 percent of patients.
Furthermore, blood pressure, trigylcerides and "bad" LDL cholesterol control has also been shown to be "generally better in the surgical group," found by authors.
Researchers also monitored the patient’s level of A1c haemoglobin in the blood, reflecting the continuous blood sugar level in the body.
Hemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7 percent, reports researchers.
After surgery, the mean hemoglobin A1c decreased from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
However, in the treatment group, this value remained at about 8 percent.
But this better "glycaemic control" - which is reflected in better levels of A1c hemoglobin - did not reduce mortality in five years, according to the chief researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The research team also compared average results with two types of operations.
After the fifth year, the group lost more weight compared to the gastricectomy group (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), reached greater reductions in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1 percent versus 2.1 percent) and had a greater likelihood of remission of diabetes (46.9 percent versus 16.7 percent).
While a new study shows no improvement in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of stronger people in Sweden, where they found that surgery leads to an extension of life, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona College or Medicine-Phoenix.
According to the Swedish study, obese people undergoing bariatric surgery had about 29 percent more chance of survival in the next 15 years, compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
