Xi calls for the opening of the economy into the wider world
It is necessary to open the economy to a wider world to boost growth, said President Xi Jinping to a group whose task is to reform management on Tuesday.
"China should be involved in attracting foreign investment and expertise and improving open policies," he said on the 16th session of the Central Head of the Group to deepen the overall reform.
Promotion of opening up in emerging reforms will give new impetus and vitality, also providing new space for economic growth, says Xi.
The lead group has adopted a number of directives, including a negative list of regulatory market access, the release of border control policy, the promotion of State-owned enterprises (SOE) to absorb private capital and the reorganisation of the registration resident system.
The declaration states that a negative list will be drawn up identifying sectors and enterprises that are outside the investment limits.
This system will be gradually tested and improved through test programmes.
This step is significant because it will give the market a greater role in resource allocation, ensuring a legal business environment and making the market more open, stating the statement.
The government will also release controls on the powers it delegates to companies and make sure that companies themselves decide how to run their business.
The declaration also states that China will allow border areas to discover new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms for promoting regional growth.
In an effort to open up the state-controlled sector, more areas will be open to private investment.
"The government will not change its policy towards foreign investment and will protect the legal interests of companies that are financed from abroad and will provide them with better services," the statement states.
In addition, it will be easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or a "green card" by optimizing requirements and simplifying the application process.
Ensuring the rights of lawyers to practice and develop professional judges and prosecutors were also discussed at the meeting.
The meeting was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang and leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, according to a statement issued after the meeting.
A new bed section may be established in the Karlovy Vary Region.
According to Deputy Governor of the Karlovy Vary Region Jakub Důmek (ČSSD), the current capacity of bed departments of two regional hospitals and two private hospitals in the region is sufficient and partial adjustments should be made on the basis of an agreement between departments of individual hospitals.
But there are also opportunities to extend care in the region.
For example, the surgical department could develop a one-day surgery centre where surgical procedures, which do not require hospitalization for more than 24 hours, would be performed according to the established concept.
In which specific hospitals should be a workplace focused on day-to-day surgery, it is not yet clear.
In the skin department of the Karlovy Vary hospital, a laser center with the possibility of using laser technology for skin diseases could be developed.
The concept also recommended the formation of an apalic center to care for patients with brain problems who are in a vegetative state.
Such a centre should be established centrally and should be an integral part of the anesthesiology-resuscitation department.
There is also the possibility of concentrating such facilities in the hospital Island, where similar care already exists.
Another bed capacity, which appears to be insufficient in the Karlovy Vary Region, is the follow-up care beds, especially those of the long-term patients (LDN), whose capacity in Nejdek is insufficient and, above all, should be closely linked to acute care beds.
Part of this device should function as beds rehabilitation and part as classic LDN beds, recommends the concept.
As he points out, the beds of follow-up care are missing mainly in the Karlovy Vary hospital.
There you could use abandoned buildings after centralization.
Last but not least in the Karlovy Vary Region, social health beds with a focus on the treatment of Alzheimer's disease are absent.
These beds are scarce throughout the Republic, so they could also serve as a so-called Alzheimer’s center for other regions.
According to the recommendations, hospitals should also prepare for the introduction of so-called follow-up beds for which European funding will be mobilised.
"It is a bed that will be linked to the areas of supespecialized care and will create room for translation of patients after surgery, for example after cardiosurgical, neurosurgical, transplant or other surgery," the regional concept of bed care describes.
New services could also be offered in the area of psychiatric care.
